===Etymology===
{{etyl|ang}} {{term|cneo|cnēo|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|knewan}} (compare Low German {{term|Knee|lang=nds}}, Dutch {{term|knie|lang=nl}}, Swedish {{term|knä|lang=sv}}), from {{proto|Indo-European|ǵnéwo-}}, a thematic derivative of {{proto|Indo-European|ǵónu-|lang=en}}. Compare {{etyl|hit|-}} {{term|genu|lang=hit}}, Latin {{term|genu|genū|lang=la}}, {{etyl|xto|-}} {{term|kanweṃ|lang=xto}} (dual), {{etyl|txb|-}} {{term|kenī|lang=txb}}, Ancient Greek {{term|γόνυ||knee|tr=góny|lang=grc}}, {{term|γωνία||corner, angle|tr=gōnía|lang=grc}}, Old Armenian {{term|ծունր||tr=cunr|lang=xcl}}, Avestan {{term||...|tr=žnum|lang=ae}}, Sanskrit {{term|जानु|tr=jānu|lang=sa}}.
